# Build output in the kit's stack-profile REFERENCE tree — CP7R5-K4-IGNORE.
#
# WHY THIS FILE EXISTS, AT THIS LEVEL. Each profile's scaffold ships its own .gitignore, but
# `incept` prunes unselected profiles and DELETES that file with the profile — so those rules are
# scoped to a shorter lifetime than the paths they protect. Anything a toolchain drops under
# profiles/ afterwards is then unignored, and a baseline `git add -A` commits it. In CP-7 run 5 that
# put generated .NET obj/ artifacts into an adopter's first commit and turned `verify.sh --require`
# RED on an untouched origin/main, failing acceptance criterion AC4.
#
# This file sits ABOVE every profile, so the prune cannot remove it, and a NEWLY ADDED profile is
# covered by construction rather than by someone remembering to add a .gitignore.
#
# THIS DOES NOT AFFECT YOUR APPLICATION SOURCE. It applies only inside profiles/ — the kit's
# reference material. Your own code lives outside this tree and is untouched.
#
# Enforced by conformance/build-output-ignored.sh, which asserts git's OWN verdict (check-ignore)
# and requires the rule to come from a tree-level file like this one. Verified at authoring time:
# ZERO of the 353 tracked files under profiles/ and conformance/fixtures/ match these patterns.
#
# Deliberately NOT here: editor/OS/user state (.idea/, *.iml, .vscode/, .DS_Store, *.csproj.user)
# and env files. Those are not build output; the repo-root .gitignore owns that policy.

# .NET — dotnet build / test / publish
bin/
obj/
publish/
TestResults/

# JVM — Maven (target/), Gradle (build/, .gradle/)
target/
build/
.gradle/

# Python — bytecode, test cache, packaging metadata, virtualenvs, coverage data
__pycache__/
.pytest_cache/
*.egg-info/
.venv/
.coverage

# Node / TypeScript
node_modules/
dist/
coverage/

# Go — `go test -coverprofile`
cover.out

# .NET coverage artifact (coverlet)
coverage.json
